Analysis of Corrected Graph Convolutions

Robert Wang111Cheriton School of Computer Science, University of Waterloo,Â Â Â Â Â Â  Aseem Baranwal222Cheriton School of Computer Science, University of Waterloo,Â Â Â Â Â Â  Kimon Fountoulakis333Cheriton School of Computer Science, University of Waterloo.
Abstract

Machine learning for node classification on graphs is a prominent area driven by applications such as recommendation systems. State-of-the-art models often use multiple graph convolutions on the data, as empirical evidence suggests they can enhance performance. However, it has been shown empirically and theoretically, that too many graph convolutions can degrade performance significantly, a phenomenon known as oversmoothing. In this paper, we provide a rigorous theoretical analysis, based on the contextual stochastic block model (CSBM), of the performance of vanilla graph convolution from which we remove the principal eigenvector to avoid oversmoothing. We perform a spectral analysis for kğ‘˜kitalic_k rounds of corrected graph convolutions, and we provide results for partial and exact classification. For partial classification, we show that each round of convolution can reduce the misclassification error exponentially up to a saturation level, after which performance does not worsen. For exact classification, we show that the separability threshold can be improved exponentially up to Oâ¢(logâ¡n/logâ¡logâ¡n)ğ‘‚ğ‘›ğ‘›O({\log{n}}/{\log\log{n}})italic_O ( roman_log italic_n / roman_log roman_log italic_n ) corrected convolutions.

1 Introduction

Graphs naturally represent complex relational information found in a plethora of applications such as social analysis Â (Backstrom and Leskovec, 2011), recommendation systemsÂ (Ying etÂ al., 2018; Borisyuk etÂ al., 2024), computer visionÂ (Monti etÂ al., 2017), materials science and chemistryÂ (Reiser etÂ al., 2022), statistical physicsÂ (Battaglia etÂ al., 2016; Bapst etÂ al., 2020), financial forensicsÂ (Zhang etÂ al., 2017; Weber etÂ al., 2019) and traffic prediction in Google MapsÂ (Derrow-Pinion etÂ al., 2021).

The abundance of relational information in combination with features of the corresponding entities has led to improved performance of machine learning models for classification and regression tasks. Central to the field of machine learning on graphs is the graph convolution operation. It has been shown empiricallyÂ (Defferrard etÂ al., 2016; Kipf and Welling, 2017; Gasteiger etÂ al., 2019; Rossi etÂ al., 2020) that using graph convolutions to the feature data enhances the prediction performance of a model, but too many graph convolutions can have the opposite effect (Oono and Suzuki, 2020; Chen etÂ al., 2020; Keriven, 2022; Wu etÂ al., 2023), an issue known as oversmoothing. Several solutions have been proposed for this problem, we refer the reader to the survey ofÂ Rusch etÂ al. (2023).

In this paper we provide a rigorous spectral analysis, based on the contextual stochastic block modelÂ (Deshpande etÂ al., 2018), to show that the oversmoothing phenomenon can be alleviated by excluding the principal eigenvectorâ€™s component from the graph convolution matrix. This is similar to the state-of-the-art normalization approach used in Zhao and Akoglu (2020); Rusch etÂ al. (2023) (PairNorm), however, our method explicitly uses the principal eigenvector. We provide below some intuition about why excluding the principal eigenvector helps to alleviate over-smoothing.

Briefly, in our results, we demonstrate that when the graph is sufficiently dense and of reasonably good quality, the corrected graph convolutions exponentially improve both partial and exact classification guarantees. However, in comparison to a similar analysis inÂ (Wu etÂ al., 2023) for vanilla graph convolutions (without correction), we show that classification accuracy does not become worse as the number of convolutions increases.

1.1 Our Contributions

In this work, we provide, to our knowledge, the first theoretical guarantees on partial and exact classification after kğ‘˜kitalic_k rounds of graph convolutions in the contextual stochastic block model. Our main result is to show that each graph convolution with the corrected matrix reduces the classification error by a multiplicative factor until a certain point of â€œsaturationâ€ and the number of convolutions required until saturation depends on the amount of input feature variance. We show that the accuracy of the linear classifier at the point of saturation only depends on the strength of the signal from the graph. This is in contrast to the uncorrected convolution matrix, which will always exhibit a decrease in classification accuracy after many convolutions. Finally, we show that given slightly stronger assumptions on graph density and signal strength, the convolved data at the point of saturation will be linearly separable with high probability. To quantify our results, we let pğ‘pitalic_p and qğ‘qitalic_q be the intra- and inter-class edge probabilities with Î³â¢(p,q)=|pâˆ’q|/(p+q)ğ›¾ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘\gamma(p,q)={|p-q|}/{(p+q)}italic_Î³ ( italic_p , italic_q ) = | italic_p - italic_q | / ( italic_p + italic_q ) being the â€œrelative signal strengthâ€ in the graph. To obtain our partial classification results, we use spectral analysis to bound the mean-squared-error between the convolved features and the true signal. For exact classification, we prove a concentration inequality on the total amount of message received by a vertex through â€œincorrect pathsâ€ of length kğ‘˜kitalic_k after kğ‘˜kitalic_k rounds of convolution through a combinatorial moment analysis. Using this, we establish entry-wise bounds on the deviation of the convolved feature vector from the true signal.

2 Literature review

Research on graph learning has increasingly focused on methods that integrate node features with relational information, particularly within the semi-supervised node classification framework, see, for example, Scarselli etÂ al. (2009); Cheng etÂ al. (2011); Gilbert etÂ al. (2012); Dang and Viennet (2012); GÃ¼nnemann etÂ al. (2013); Yang etÂ al. (2013); Hamilton etÂ al. (2017); Jin etÂ al. (2019); Mehta etÂ al. (2019); Chien etÂ al. (2022); Yan etÂ al. (2021). These studies have underscored the empirical advantages of incorporating graph structures when available.

The literature also addresses the expressive capacity (Lu etÂ al., 2017; Balcilar etÂ al., 2021) and generalization potential (Maskey etÂ al., 2022) of Graph Neural Networks (GNNs), including challenges like oversmoothing (Keriven, 2022; Xu etÂ al., 2021; Oono and Suzuki, 2020; Li etÂ al., 2018; Rusch etÂ al., 2023). In our paper, we ground our work on the contextual stochastic block model (Deshpande etÂ al., 2018), a widely used statistical framework for analyzing graph learning and inference problems. Recent theoretical studies have extensively used the CSBM to illustrate several statistical, information-theoretic, and combinatorial results on relational data accompanied by node features. In Deshpande etÂ al. (2018); Lu and Sen (2020), the authors investigate the classification thresholds for accurately classifying a significant portion of nodes from this model, given linear sample complexity and large but bounded degree. Additionally, Hou etÂ al. (2020) introduces graph smoothness metrics to quantify the utility of graphical information. Further developments in Chien etÂ al. (2021, 2022); Baranwal etÂ al. (2021, 2023a) extend the application of CSBM, establishing exact classification thresholds for graph convolutions in multi-layer networks, accompanied by generalization guarantees. A theoretical exploration of the graph attention mechanism (GAT) is provided by Fountoulakis etÂ al. (2023), delineating conditions under which attention can improve node classification tasks. More recently, Baranwal etÂ al. (2023b) provide the locally Bayes optimal message-passing architecture for node classification for the general CSBM.

In this paper, we provide exact and partial classification guarantees for multiple graph convolution operations. Previous investigations have often been confined to a few convolution layers, limiting the understanding of their effects on variance reduction (see, for example, Baranwal etÂ al. (2023a)). Our findings contribute a novel spectral perspective on graph convolutions, describing how the fraction of recoverable nodes is influenced by the signal-to-noise ratio in the node features and the scaled difference between intra- and inter-class edge probabilities. We also demonstrate that the oversmoothing phenomenon can be alleviated by excluding the principal eigenvectorâ€™s component from the adjacency matrix â€“ a strategy somewhat akin to the normalization approach used in Zhao and Akoglu (2020) (PairNorm), albeit our method explicitly uses the principal eigenvector and is grounded in rigorous spectral justifications.

In a relatively recent work (Wu etÂ al., 2023) the authors rigorously analyze the phenomenon of oversmoothing in GNNs for the 2-block CSBM by identifying two competing effects of graph convolutions: the mixing effect, which homogenizes node representations across different classes, and the denoising effect, which homogenizes node representations within the same class. Their analysis shows that oversmoothing occurs when the mixing effect dominates the denoising effect, and they quantify the number of layers required for this transition. In contrast, we work with the corrected graph convolution in the 2-block CSBM and show that it improves performance exponentially up to saturation, after which more convolutions do not improve nor degrade performance. On a technical level, the previous work only analyzes the distribution of a single nodeâ€™s feature values after convolution and does not take into account correlations between nodes. In our work, we use spectral analysis of higher powers of the convolution matrix, which takes into account correlations between nodes to obtain our partial classification results over the whole dataset. To handle the modified convolution in the exact classification setting, we analyze the error more directly through matrix perturbation analysis rather than trying to directly count the higher-order neighbors of each vertex as in previous works (Baranwal etÂ al., 2023a; Wu etÂ al., 2023).

4 Results and Interpretation

In our analysis, there are two types of objectives. In the exact classification objective, the aim is to exactly recover Sğ‘†Sitalic_S and Tğ‘‡Titalic_T with probability 1âˆ’oâ¢(1)1ğ‘œ11-o(1)1 - italic_o ( 1 ). In the partial classification, or â€œdetectionâ€ problem, the goal is to correctly classify 1âˆ’oâ¢(1)1ğ‘œ11-o(1)1 - italic_o ( 1 ) fraction of vertices correctly with probability 1âˆ’oâ¢(1)1ğ‘œ11-o(1)1 - italic_o ( 1 ). We begin by stating our results for the partial classification regime. For ease of notation, we will assume p>qğ‘ğ‘p>qitalic_p > italic_q from this point forward. We show in AppendixÂ B that this assumption is made without loss of generality.

4.1 Discussion on our Assumptions

Both TheoremÂ 4.1 and TheoremÂ 4.2 require a lower bound of Î³â‰¥Ï‰â¢(1/nâ¢p)ğ›¾ğœ”1ğ‘›ğ‘\gamma\geq\omega({1}/{\sqrt{np}})italic_Î³ â‰¥ italic_Ï‰ ( 1 / square-root start_ARG italic_n italic_p end_ARG ), and this is to ensure that the signal from the graph is strong enough so that a convolution does not destroy the signal from the data. Also, implicit in the probability bound of TheoremÂ 4.1 and in TheoremÂ 4.2, is the assumption that our signal-to-noise ratio, âˆ¥Î¼âˆ’Î½âˆ¥/Ïƒdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğœ‡ğœˆğœ\left\lVert\mu-\nu\right\rVert/\sigmaâˆ¥ italic_Î¼ - italic_Î½ âˆ¥ / italic_Ïƒ, is at least Ï‰â¢(1/n)ğœ”1ğ‘›\omega(1/\sqrt{n})italic_Ï‰ ( 1 / square-root start_ARG italic_n end_ARG ) so the feature noise does not completely drown out the signal. Our lower-bound assumption on pğ‘pitalic_p is to ensure concentration in the behavior of the degrees and the adjacency matrix towards their expectation. In TheoremÂ 4.2, we also assume that k=Oâ¢(logâ¡n)ğ‘˜ğ‘‚ğ‘›k=O(\log{n})italic_k = italic_O ( roman_log italic_n ). This is done mainly for technical reasons of our proof but we note that this assumption is made without loss of generality because as mentioned, the bound in TheoremÂ 4.2 does not improve for kâ‰¥logâ¡nğ‘˜ğ‘›k\geq\log{n}italic_k â‰¥ roman_log italic_n. Finally, we note that the case p>qğ‘ğ‘p>qitalic_p > italic_q corresponds to a homophilous graph, and the case p<qğ‘ğ‘p<qitalic_p < italic_q corresponds to a heterophilous graph (see Luan etÂ al. (2021); Ma etÂ al. (2022) for more). For binary classification, it has been shown (Baranwal etÂ al., 2023a) that one can assume p>qğ‘ğ‘p>qitalic_p > italic_q without loss of generality and make corresponding adjustments in the classifier. As such, we assume that p>qğ‘ğ‘p>qitalic_p > italic_q. For more detail regarding this assumption, see AppendixÂ B.

5 One-Dimensional CSBM

In Baranwal etÂ al. (2021), the authors showed that analyzing the linear classifier for the mğ‘šmitalic_m-dimensional CSBM reduces to analyzing the 1111-dimensional model. Our argument is inspired by the proof of the central limit theorem using pairing partitions, as in chapter 8 of Nica and Speicher (2010).

8 Experiments

In this section, we demonstrate our results empirically. For synthetic data, we show TheoremsÂ 4.1 andÂ 4.2 for linear binary classification. For real data, we show that removing the principal component of the adjacency matrix exhibits positive effects on multi-class node classification problems as well.

8.1 Synthetic Data

For synthetic data from the CSBM, we demonstrate the benefits of removing the principal component of the adjacency matrix before performing convolutions for both variants of convolution described in EquationÂ 1. We choose n=2000ğ‘›2000n=2000italic_n = 2000 nodes with 20202020 features for each node, sampled from a Gaussian mixture. The intra-edge probability is fixed to p=Oâ¢(log3â¡n/n)ğ‘ğ‘‚superscript3ğ‘›ğ‘›p=O(\log^{3}n/n)italic_p = italic_O ( roman_log start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_n / italic_n ). We perform linear classification to demonstrate the results in TheoremÂ 4.1 and TheoremÂ 4.2, training a one-layer GCN network both with and without the corrected convolutions and perform an empirical comparison.

We provide plots for two different settings: (1) Fix Î³=|pâˆ’q|/(p+q)=2/3ğ›¾ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘23\gamma={|p-q|}/({p+q})=2/3italic_Î³ = | italic_p - italic_q | / ( italic_p + italic_q ) = 2 / 3 and vary signal-to-noise ratio of the node features, â€–Î¼âˆ’Î½â€–/Ïƒnormğœ‡ğœˆğœ\|\mu-\nu\|/\sigmaâˆ¥ italic_Î¼ - italic_Î½ âˆ¥ / italic_Ïƒ, for different number of convolutions. We observe in FigureÂ 1 that as the number of convolutions increases, the original GCN (Kipf and Welling, 2017) (in blue) starts performing poorly, while the corrected versions (in orange and green) retain the accuracy for lower signal-to-noise ratio; (2) Fix â€–Î¼âˆ’Î½â€–/Ïƒ=1normğœ‡ğœˆğœ1{\|\mu-\nu\|}/{\sigma}=1âˆ¥ italic_Î¼ - italic_Î½ âˆ¥ / italic_Ïƒ = 1 and vary the graph relative signal strength, Î³ğ›¾\gammaitalic_Î³, for different number of convolutions. We observe the same trends in this setting, as depicted in FigureÂ 2. The vertical lines represent the threshold for exact classification from TheoremÂ 4.2.

8.2 Real Data

Similar to synthetic data, we compare the results for corrected graph convolution to the original GCN on the following real graph benchmarks datasets: CORA, CiteSeer, and Pubmed citation networks (Sen etÂ al., 2008). It is observed in FigureÂ 3 that correcting the convolution as in EquationÂ 1 by removing the principal component performs better as the number of layers increases, even for a multi-class setting, where we perform one convolution at each layer.

Note that in FigureÂ 3, we see that overall the accuracy of every learning method decreases as the number of convolutions increases but the corrected convolutions converge to an accuracy much higher than that of the uncorrected convolution. This is attributed to the fact that for multi-class classification, the important information about class memberships is captured by the top Cğ¶Citalic_C eigenvectors (except the first one) where Cğ¶Citalic_C is the number of classes (Lee etÂ al., 2014). Since the limiting behavior of many rounds of convolutions is akin to projecting the features onto the second eigenvector, we only expect this to capture partial information about the multi-class structure.

9 Conclusion and Future Work

In this study, we utilized spectral methods to obtain partial and exact classification results for the linear classifier with corrected convolution matrices in the 2-block CSBM. Our spectral approach highlights, theoretically, how removing the top eigenvector can mitigate oversmoothing and improve classification accuracy. We prove that the removal of the top eigenvector results in reducing feature variance and correcting the asymptotic behavior of many rounds of convolution towards the second, rather than the top eigenvector of the adjacency matrix. We hope our analysis can lead to further developments in theoretical and practical studies of GNNs. On the theoretical side, we believe our analysis can be extended to more general models. One potential avenue would be to analyze the multi-class CSBM using more sophisticated architectures, like the spectral convolutional network with low-degree matrix polynomials (Defferrard etÂ al., 2016) and non-linear activation functions.

Note that the case p>qğ‘ğ‘p>qitalic_p > italic_q corresponds to a homophilous graph, and the case p<qğ‘ğ‘p<qitalic_p < italic_q corresponds to a heterophilous graph (see Luan etÂ al. [2021], Ma etÂ al. [2022] for more), however, for binary classification, it has been shown [Baranwal etÂ al., 2023a] that once can assume p>qğ‘ğ‘p>qitalic_p > italic_q without loss of generality, and make corresponding adjustments in the classifier. Indeed in our case, if p<qğ‘ğ‘p<qitalic_p < italic_q then we can take âˆ’A~~ğ´-\tilde{A}- over~ start_ARG italic_A end_ARG as our convolution matrix so that its maximum modulus eigenvalue is positive. Moreover, since our signal, sğ‘ sitalic_s, is centered, taking a convolution with A~~ğ´\tilde{A}over~ start_ARG italic_A end_ARG is equivalent to taking a convolution with âˆ’A~~ğ´-\tilde{A}- over~ start_ARG italic_A end_ARG. Thus, we can assume without loss of generality that Î³ğ›¾\gammaitalic_Î³ is always non-negative, i.e. p>qğ‘ğ‘p>qitalic_p > italic_q for the rest of our analysis.
